<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-07-19T22:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-07-19T22:00:00-05:00" n="211" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d211">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/8860: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Tientsin</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Caldwell</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tientsin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-07-20T11:00:00+08:00">July 20, 1937—11
                                        a.m.</date><lb/>[Received July 20—7:35 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>Six thousand Japanese troops with twenty-four 75-millimeter field
                                pieces and miscellaneous equipment including a number of machine
                                guns and trench mortars arrived here from Manchuria during the past
                                2 days; about 3,000 of them left here last night on foot by the
                                Peiping Highway. Unconfirmed report is that large number of Japanese
                                troops will land at Tangku within a few days.</p>
                            <p>Japanese military authorities have imposed censorship of mails at the
                                central post office here since July 18th.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Caldwell</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>